## Project Setup

```bash
dotnet new mcpserver -n MyApiMcpServer
cd MyApiMcpServer
```

## Tool Class — `ApiTools.cs`

```csharp
using ModelContextProtocol.Server;
using System.ComponentModel;
using System.Text.Json;

[McpServerToolType]
public class ApiTools(HttpClient httpClient, ILogger<ApiTools> logger)
{
    [McpServerTool, Description("Get a user by ID from the REST API.")]
    public async Task<string> GetUser(
        [Description("The numeric user ID")] int userId,
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        logger.LogInformation("Fetching user {UserId}", userId);
        var json = await httpClient.GetStringAsync(
            $"/users/{userId}", cancellationToken);
        return json;
    }

    [McpServerTool, Description("Create a new user in the REST API.")]
    public async Task<string> CreateUser(
        [Description("Display name for the user")] string name,
        [Description("User email address")] string email,
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        var payload = JsonSerializer.Serialize(new { name, email });
        var content = new StringContent(payload, System.Text.Encoding.UTF8, "application/json");
        var response = await httpClient.PostAsync("/users", content, cancellationToken);
        response.EnsureSuccessStatusCode();
        return await response.Content.ReadAsStringAsync(cancellationToken);
    }
}
```

## `Program.cs` — stdio transport

```csharp
using Microsoft.Extensions.DependencyInjection;
using Microsoft.Extensions.Hosting;
using Microsoft.Extensions.Logging;
using ModelContextProtocol.Server;

var builder = Host.CreateApplicationBuilder(args);

// CRITICAL: log to stderr only — stdout is the JSON-RPC transport
builder.Logging.AddConsole(options =>
    options.LogToStandardErrorThreshold = LogLevel.Trace);

builder.Services.AddHttpClient<ApiTools>(client =>
{
    client.BaseAddress = new Uri("https://api.example.com");
});

builder.Services.AddMcpServer()
    .WithStdioServerTransport()
    .WithToolsFromAssembly();

await builder.Build().RunAsync();
```

---

## How DI Works for MCP Tools

The SDK supports **two injection styles**:

| Style | Class type | How services arrive |
|---|---|---|
| **Constructor injection** | Non-static class (shown above) | Services in the constructor — `ApiTools(HttpClient http)` |
| **Method parameter injection** | Static class | Services as method params — `DoWork(HttpClient http, string input)` |

**Key rule:** The SDK automatically distinguishes DI services from tool parameters. Types registered in the DI container (`HttpClient`, `ILogger<T>`, `IMcpServer`, `CancellationToken`, `IProgress<>`) are **injected at runtime** and **never appear** in the tool's JSON schema. Only parameters with `[Description]` are exposed to the LLM.

So in `GetUser` above, the LLM sees one parameter (`userId`), while `httpClient`, `logger`, and `cancellationToken` are all resolved by DI/framework automatically.

**Registration flow:**
1. `AddHttpClient<ApiTools>()` registers `HttpClient` with the base address
2. `AddMcpServer().WithToolsFromAssembly()` discovers `[McpServerToolType]` classes
3. When the LLM calls a tool, the SDK resolves the class from DI, injects services, and invokes the method
